Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis

Context

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

percentage_not_given = (df['rating'] == 'Not given').sum() / len(df['rating']) * 100
print('Percentage of "Not given" entries: ' + str(percentage_not_given))

# First, backup the column original data
df['rating_original'] = df['rating']

# Create a column coercing "Not given" to NaN
df['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(df['rating'].replace('Not given', np.nan), errors='coerce')
df['rating'] = df['rating'].fillna(df['rating'].median())
df['rating'] = df['rating'].astype(int)

Mode imputation is mostly for categorical data and we are dealing with numerical data.

Because we are dealing with ordinal values, left-skewed (with more high ratings) and having a large number of missing values, I will use Median Imputation. Using the mean imputation could result in a value that is not a real rating (for example, 4.4).

However, one drawback is that the median value will be over-represented.

Because I have determined that 'rating' has missing data and that I am using Median Imputation to treat the data, I will replace 'Not Given' with NaN,convert the column to numeric, replace the NaN with the median value and convert the column to int type.

    errors='coerce'
)

numerical_cols = ['cost_of_the_order', 'food_preparation_time', 'delivery_time', 'rating_original_numerical']

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]

In[31]:
def calculate_commission_perc(cost):
    if cost > 20:
        return 0.25
    elif cost > 5:
        return 0.15
    else:
        return 0.0

df['commission_perc'] = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(calculate_commission_perc)
df['commission'] = df['cost_of_the_order'] * df['commission_perc']
net_revenue = df['commission'].sum()
print('The net revenue generated by the company is ' + str(net_revenue) + '$.')

The net revenue generated by the company is 6166.303$.

Observations: The net revenue generated by the company is 6166.303$.

Conclusion and Recommendations

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]

Conclusions:

  • Customer satisfaction is generally high, with most rated orders receiving 4 or 5 stars. However, around 39% of the orders are not rated.
  • While food preparation time shows no direct impact on ratings, faster deliveries tend to correlate with higher customer ratings (although not very significantly).
  • Deliveries take longer during weekdays compared to weekends, despite high ratings across both periods. The majority of order activity is concentrated on weekends.
  • There are not many frequent customers; the distribution is right-skewed, indicating that a large number of customers place only a few orders.
  • 'American', 'Japanese', 'Italian' and 'Chinese' types dominate order volume, while 'Spanish' and 'Vietnamese' cuisines show slightly lower and more varied ratings.
  • Finally, around 10% of all orders take over 60 minutes for combined preparation and delivery.

Recommendations:

  • Enhance Weekday delivery efficiency: Investigate the root causes behind longer weekday delivery times (e.g.: traffic, not enough drivers) and work on mitigation strategies.
  • Improve Customer Feedback: Implement initiatives to increase the volume of rated orders, addressing the current 39% unrated orders by simplifying the rating process or offering small discounts.
  • Invest in improving Cuisine quality: Conduct a focused analysis to understand the underlying reasons for the relatively lower and more varied ratings observed for 'Spanish' and 'Vietnamese' cuisines.
  • Optimize orders complete time: Identify the specific restaurants that contribute to the 10% of orders exceeding 60 minutes for combined preparation and delivery. Understand why they take longer and work on reducing these times.
  • Cultivate Customer Loyalty and Frequency: Implement a loyalty program to attract more regular customers or provide personal recommendations, addressing the current right-skewed distribution of orders per customer.
